    <p class="note-sm" >
      The pink tax holds women to a financial and economical  disadvantage. Is the pink tax real? If so, how can we  mitigate or eliminate its effects on low or middle income women? Let’s dive into it Image credit: [HealthLine]

    </p>
  


  </header>

  
    <p>In 2019, newfound attention turned to an economic phenomenon that had slipped under the radar. Half of the national population was spending significantly more on day-to-day purchases, such as hygiene products, apparel, and even children’s toys. They made up our country’s teachers, laborers, politicians, daughters, wives, and mothers. And on average, they spend almost $1,351 more a year on extra costs compared to men.</p>


    
    
